1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
Often we stay so close to a problem for so long that we can't see new solutions or new approaches.

2
00:00:06,575 --> 00:00:13,105
An engineer friend was retained a few weeks ago to design a distinctly new aluminum structure.

3
00:00:13,295 --> 00:00:18,865
In fact, nothing even resembling it had even been developed or designed before.

4
00:00:19,135 --> 00:00:24,385
I saw him just a few days ago, and I asked him how his new building was coming along.

5
00:00:24,815 --> 00:00:26,704
Not too well, he replied.

6
00:00:26,974 --> 00:00:30,545
I guess I haven't spent enough time with my garden this summer.

7
00:00:30,735 --> 00:00:37,744
When I live with tough design problems for a long stretch, I've got to get away and let some new ideas soak in.

8
00:00:38,335 --> 00:00:48,065
You'd be surprised, he continued, to know how many engineering ideas come to me when I'm just sitting beside a tree holding a water hose on the grass.

9
00:00:48,974 --> 00:00:55,345
President Eisenhower once was asked at a news conference why he took so many weekend vacations.

10
00:00:55,615 --> 00:01:01,185
His answer is good advice for everybody who wants to maximize his creative ability.

11
00:01:01,615 --> 00:01:10,224
Mr. Eisenhower said, I do not believe that any individual, whether he is running General Motors or the United States of America,

12
00:01:10,335 --> 00:01:15,744
can do the best job just by sitting at a desk and putting his face in a bunch of papers.

13
00:01:16,015 --> 00:01:28,385
Actually, the president ought to be trying to keep his mind free of inconsequential details and doing his own thinking on the basic principles and factors so that he can make clear and better judgments.

14
00:01:29,535 --> 00:01:37,264
A former business associate of mine takes a 72-hour out-of-town vacation with his wife once each month.

15
00:01:37,775 --> 00:01:46,464
He found this backing off and starting afresh increased his mental efficiency, thereby making him more valuable to his clients.

16
00:01:47,295 --> 00:01:51,104
When you hit a snag, don't throw up the whole project.

17
00:01:51,214 --> 00:01:54,785
Instead, back off, get mentally refreshed.

18
00:01:55,135 --> 00:02:00,224
Try something as simple as playing some music or taking a walk or a short nap.

19
00:02:00,495 --> 00:02:06,305
Then, when you tackle it again, the solution often comes almost before you know it.

20
00:02:07,375 --> 00:02:11,345
Seeing the good side pays off in big situations, too.
